<DOCNO> AP881207-0002 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the moslem half of lebanons divided 
government feuded wednesday over a proposal to take control of the 
nations embattled central bank and block funds for christian 
military forces 
militia head walid jumblatt a druse moslem who also heads 
several government portfolios threatened tuesday to force 
replacement of bank management if it transferred money to christian 
units of the lebanese army the daily annahar newspaper reported 
however an aide to prime minister salim hoss who leads the 
nations moslem cabinet quoted hoss as saying wednesday that the 
bank should be preserved intact for the sake of national unity 
if the central bank collapses the whole country will collapse 
with it said the aide who spoke on condition of anonymity 
a few hours after jumblatts speech a rocketpropelled grenade 
slammed into the central bank building in moslem west beirut it 
caused severe damage but no casualties police said 
there was no immediate claim of responsibility for the attack 
lebanons christian leaders also lashed out the bank over the 
weekend a source close to michael aoun leader of the rival 
christian military cabinet said bank officials were pressured by 
prosyrian leaders to block a fund transfer requested by aoun he 
was reported to ask for the money to repair jet fighters controlled 
by christian units of the lebanese army 
the central bank made no comment on the reports 
lebanon has been without a head of state since sept 23 when the 
sixyear term of former president amin gemayel expired sectarian 
skirmishing prevented election of a successor 
gemayel then appointed aoun a maronite christian as prime 
minister of an interim cabinet but prosyrian moslem leaders 
rejected the move and declared sole allegiance to hoss existing 
cabinet 
rivalry between the two cabinets has further divided the army and 
police along sectarian lines with about 40000 troops in lebanon 
syria is the main power broker in lebanon 
</TEXT>
