<DOCNO> AP881207-0003 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a winding street lined with small houses and 
bearing roy orbisons name is this towns only monument to the 
legendary singer and songwriter who grew up here 
but the west texas town of 1200 where the high school football 
stadium is the biggest thing in town and the oil field pumpjacks and 
scrub brush stand high on the horizon provided the musical grist 
for the man known for his black garb wraparound sunglasses and 
haunting vocals 
orbison who sang such hits as pretty woman and crying 
died of a heart attack late tuesday in hendersonville tenn he was 
52 
wink residents remember orbison as someone whose extraordinary 
talent surfaced early 
in high school he and some friends formed the wink westerners 
which played country and western music at school dances and later 
had a radio and television show sponsored by a furniture store in 
nearby odessa 
the band formed when orbison was a sophomore made its debut at 
a wink high school assembly and went on to play dance halls and bars 
in surrounding towns such as iraan crane and jal the group changed 
its name to the teen kings after its five members graduated and 
played a newer kind of music rock n roll 
after a trip to nashville and a national tour they came back 
to wink and all of them were driving cadillacs said john paul 
pitts a former wink resident who lived one house away from orbison 
i used to come out of my house and see roy in the back seat of 
his car practicing the guitar because his house was so small 
said pitts who wore orbisons sport coat for his high school 
graduation because he didnt own one 
years before forming the band orbison played his guitar and sang 
outside the local drug store 
people would throw him nickels and quarters said jl dodd 
principal of wink high school who taught orbison in two classes 
orbisons musical ambition was evidenced in the verse beneath his 
senior picture in his 1954 high school yearbook to lead a western 
band is his after school wish and of course to marry a 
beautiful dish 
the orbison family came to the area from vernon during the oil 
boom of the 1940s orbisons father orvie lee worked in the 
permian basin oil fields but found time to teach his son to play the 
guitar at age 6 
orbison last visited west texas for an oil aid concert in midland 
last year to benefit economically stricken oilfield workers 
i never thought that success changed him said bill beckham 
publisher of the wink bulletin and the winkler county news who 
attended high school with orbison wink was always home for roy 
even though he had not been there for many years 
last year the town changed the name of langley way where the 
singer had lived to roy orbison drive the shotgun house his family 
occupied is no longer standing 
wink officials said wednesday they were planning a memorial 
service for orbison but details had not been worked out yet 
</TEXT>
