<DOCNO> AP881207-0008 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
secular israelis are organizing to stop a 
campaign by the ultraorthodox to close all forms of entertainment 
from soccer stadiums to cafes on the jewish sabbath 
secular jews find the prospect even more offensive because few 
ultraorthodox do army service in a nation that fights to survive 
and has experienced four wars in its 40 years 
some of the alarm appears exaggerated but many israelis feel 
political success by the religious fundamentalists could alter the 
character of the jewish state discouraging immigration and even 
provoking a flight of talented people 
about 70 percent of israels 35 million jews are nonobservant 
despite that majority they were passive in past years when the 
orthodox obtained such concessions as stopping the national airline 
el al from flying on the sabbath sundown friday to sundown 
saturday 
demands by four small religious parties with the balance of power 
in the parliament elected nov 1 however have have prompted the 
first largescale organization of secular jews 
one group is hemdat a privately financed association formed to 
safeguard scientific cultural and religious freedoms 
it formed an emergency committee called freedom to organize 
feminists nonorthodox rabbis army officers and scholars against 
religious legislation proposed by the ultraorthodox 
the orthodox may be strong in the parliament but out in the 
street they are weak said zamira segev a hemdat coordinator 
the moment we organize and we are insistent we will win 
many feel religious coercion contradicts the vision of israels 
socialist pioneers who sought freedom from religious strictures as 
well as national liberation 
one rallying point of the secular is fear that laws closing 
stadiums theaters restaurants bars and other public places on the 
sabbath would encourage emigration 
after the elections a lot of people said thats it im 
leaving segev said i cant believe people will actually go 
but its a burning subject 
educators say the ultraorthodox might divert government funds 
from universities forcing scholars to seek opportunities abroad 
the ultraorthodox consider the universities to be hotbeds of 
secularism and would love to cut them down said lee levine an 
archaeology professor at hebrew university 
exemption of the ultraorthodox from army service creates strong 
feeling 
other israeli men do three years of compulsory service followed 
by up to 62 days a year of reserve duty but ultraorthodox students 
often defer service until age 26 after that they either do not 
serve at all or are not required to do the full three years 
about 10000 people rallied in kings of israel square in tel aviv 
last month to protest such deferments which have totaled about 
19000 in 1988 
i dont understand why i had to fight and lose my legs and 
lose my friends while someone sits in school and prays a veteran 
identified only as maoziya told the applauding protesters 
he lost both legs an arm and an eye during the threeyear 
invasion and occupation of lebanon that ended in june 1985 maoziya 
said he still was doing reserve duty and so could the ultraorthodox 
judaisms more liberal reform and conservative movements are 
active in the effort to stop religious laws 
as a conservative rabbi i am not in favor of operating cinemas 
and ruining the nature of the sabbath but i feel the jewish 
religion can compete on the open market of ideas said rabbi 
philip spectre chairman of the freedom committee it does not 
have to be enforced by legislation 
the orthodox establishment has a monopoly on israels religious 
affairs it has barred liberal rabbis from performing marriages or 
burials and made the liberal movements ineligible for state 
education funds 
four religious political parties won 18 seats in the 120member 
knesset on nov 1 enough to force concessions from prime minister 
yitzhak shamir if he includes them in a rightwing coalition 
topping the orthodox agenda is a law recognizing only conversions 
to judaism performed by orthodox rabbis 
among people who would not longer be considered jewish under such 
a statute is david codding a britishborn immigrant who has lived 
in israel for 17 years served in a combat army unit and raised a 
family here he was converted to judaism by a nonorthodox rabbi 
the implications of that law mean that if god forbid i were 
killed in the service of this country i would not be interred in 
consecrated ground codding wrote in a letter to the jerusalem 
post newspaper 
targets for the ultraorthodox are less lofty but would have 
greater inmmediate effect they want to reverse the victory secular 
jews won in persuading some jerusalem theaters to show movies on 
friday nights 
some religious parties also favor making rulings of the 
rabbinical courts immune to reversal by the supreme court critics 
say that would enable rabbis to annul foreign marriages and 
divorces creating a maze of bigamy unresolved divorce settlements 
and child custody disputes 
ultraorthodox leaders say they are trying to preserve the jewish 
nature of israel not to coerce the secular 
we dont want to impose on the private life of any person 
said rabbi menachem porush a leading member of the ultraorthodox 
party augudat israel 
their opponents worry about a hidden agenda and satirists paint 
scenes of a country where secular books and mixed bathing are 
banned synagogue attendance is mandatory married women must shave 
their heads in accordance with religious rulings on modesty and 
rabbis inspect homes to make sure dietary laws are observed 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

