<TEXT>
us officials have predicted for months that 
kremlin leader mikhail s gorbachev would announce a unilateral cut 
in soviet troops in eastern europe a move that could reap public 
relations profits for moscow and allow it to divert money into 
domestic programs 
a number of soviet and american officials thought gorbachev would 
use his speech before the united nations general assembly today to 
announce a decision by the ruling politburo to go ahead with the 
cuts which have been opposed by senior red army generals 
following the sept 30 politburo shakeup that strengthened 
gorbachevs hand the ruling body agreed to cuts in the armed 
forces which currently number 56 million men and women according 
to published reports in the washington post and new york times 
the cuts are most likely in eastern europe where the soviets 
have about 500000 troops and along the soviet border with china 
gorbachev and his aides have been hinting at such reductions in 
what they describe as a new military doctrine of reasonable 
sufficiency based on an ability to defend against attack rather 
than to mount a major offensive 
many us officials thought gorbachev would announce troop cuts 
during the most recent summit last may in moscow 
but senior military officials led by the chief of staff marshal 
sergei akhromeyev have opposed any decrease in soviet forces 
without a reduction by the west 
in accordance with the new defensive doctrine we are beginning 
to introduce some changes in organizational structure of the soviet 
armed forces in order to impart a defensive nature to the armed 
forces but this will demand some time akhromeyev said during a 
visit last july to the pentagon 
the complete realization of the changes bears on bilateral 
steps he said therefore we must sit at the negotiating table 
and address the outstanding issues between us he said in a 
statement clearly aimed at discouraging speculation of any 
unilateral soviet cuts 
defense secretary frank c carlucci and other senior us 
officials have been watching soviet statements closely but say they 
have not yet seen any changes in the size armaments and deployment 
of the red army 
red army generals also opposed similar cuts in their forces made 
in the mid1950s by thensoviet leader nikita s khrushchev 
the kremlin could gain from unilateral troop cuts in eastern 
europe and along the chinese border 
such a move would improve the atmosphere for a spring summit 
scheduled between gorbachev and chinese leader deng xiaoping and 
would further enhance the popularity of gorbachev in western europe 
where he is already regarded more favorably than is reagan 
according to us government polls 
cutting conventional forces also could yield economic benefits 
for gorbachev whose government admitted this year for the first 
time that it was facing a budget deficit 
