mkhatshwa was secretarygeneral of the south african catholic 
bishops conference when the alleged assault took place aug 21 
1986 after police detained him without charge in pretoria 
mkhatshwa now secretarygeneral of the institute for contextual 
theology said police took him to an unknown destination and forced 
him to stand blindfolded and handcuffed for about 30 hours while 
authorities used an unspecified instrument to hurt his genitals 
his interrogators repeatedly insulted him and fired shots near 
his ears mkhatshwa said 
his allegations were made in a civil damage claim the attorney 
general told mkhatshwas lawyers that six men were charged with 
criminal injury in the case one police captain paid a 90 admission 
of guilt fine and the other men were absolved of any wrongdoing 
without a trial 
police did not comment on the case tuesday 
the government has paid thousands of dollars in outofcourt 
settlements this year to resolve cases of alleged police torture 
under the arrangement the government does not admit liability 
an estimated 30000 people have been detained without charge for 
varying lengths during the 29 monthold state of emergency about 
1000 people still are in detention 
