<TEXT>
two medical illustrators whose drawings updating 
pictures of longmissing children have helped find some of the 
youngsters are speeding up their work with computers 
lewis sadler and scott barrows of the university of illinois used 
to take 20 hours to prepare a drawing now with a computer they 
can do it in about 20 minutes 
using old photos they measure 48 anatomical landmarks nose 
size width of the mouth and spacing of the eyes for example and 
expand them to account for growth producing a picture often 
remarkably similar to the childs appearance 
with a computer the photographs can be scanned by lasers in 
seconds and the facial information transferred into software 
programs that create images of missing children as they age 
john rabin deputy director of the national center for missing 
and exploited children in washington said sadler and barrows 
computerized system will vastly enhance the centers efforts to find 
more than 7500 children 
its like going from a quill pen to stateoftheart equipment 
the speed alone is going to be amazing rabin said 
sadler said that the finished product will look more like a 
photograph and that the computer isnt as prone to error as humans 
in calculating childrens features 
the new computer supported by a 13 million grant from the 
american telephone amp telgraph co goes into fulltime work in 
january sadler said tuesday 
so far the data on anatomical landmarks collected by 
anthropologists dentists and plastic surgeons is complete enough 
only to make pictures of white nonhispanic children updated 
pictures of blacks hispanics and asians will have to wait for more 
information 
the work of the two scientists has drawn national attention 
of the approximately 80 missing children drawn by sadler and 
barrows since they began their work in 1985 24 of the children have 
been found sadler said of those the drawings played at least some 
role in 17 cases he said 
in one case their drawing of a 13yearold girl who had been 
missing since she was 3 was the clue that brought her home 
in another case two sisters missing for 7 years were located 
just 20 minutes after drawings by sadler and barrows were broadcast 
on national television 
</TEXT>
