<TEXT>
the estonian parliament adopted a 
constitutional amendment today making estonian the state language 
but it postponed action on a law that would force the republics 
russian residents to learn the language 
the vote on the amendment was 20449 with four abstentions that 
was 14 more than the twothirds required to pass a constitutional 
amendment 
it was the widest margin of disagreement yet in the estonian 
parliament officially called the supreme soviet which has only 
recently begun to debate issues that it once rubberstamped 
the proposed law would have required nonnative workers including 
police shop clerks and doctors to learn estonian 
many migrants from other parts of the soviet union have not 
learned the local language even after years of residence in the tiny 
republic on the baltic sea the law will be reconsidered in january 
the language proposal generated considerable controversy 
many of the russian migrants preferred not to learn a new 
language and the native population feared it would soon be 
outnumbered in its own homeland and that its language and culture 
would die 
a russian organization called intermovement denounced the 
language proposal as divisive at a rally last week some of its 
members went so far as to call it an incitement to ethnic hatred 
hundreds of thousands of russians poured into estonia for 
wellpaid factory jobs largely from now nearly deserted farming 
villages said estonian engineer martin kuusk if they want to 
stay they must absorb our culture he said if they do not want 
to learn their country is in the neighborhood 
a supreme soviet deputy with the russian name of mayakovsky 
suggested adding a line defining russian as the international 
language of the soviet union but the proposal was defeated by a 
vote of 14135 
the former leader of estonia communist party first secretary 
karl vaino knew little of the republics language and for most of 
the 1980s all government documents were written only in russian 
vaino was replaced last summer by a reformer and native estonian 
vaino vyalyas 
estonia joins four other republics that declared state languages 
the nearby baltic republic of lithuania passed its law in recent 
weeks armenia azerbaijan and georgia have had similar 
constitutional amendments since 1978 
at a special meeting of the estonian communist party this 
morning recently elected prime minister indrek toome resigned his 
party job as ideology secretary he was replaced by mikk titma one 
of four men who devised estonias currently debated proposal for 
economic reform 
titmas elevation to the party secretariat was a dramatic 
promotion because he had not even been a member of the partys 
central committee 
on tuesday estonias parliament banned further industrial 
development in an ecologically devastated area of the republic 
putting itself on a collision course with moscow ministries 
the action marked a first exercise of the republics newly 
declared sovereignty in all but military and foreign policy matters 
the republics parliament on nov 16 declared estonias 
sovereignty over all its internal affairs in moscow the executive 
council of the national parliament promptly deemed the action 
illegal 
but the estonians who number 16 million have refused to abide 
by the kremlin directive and their parliament has even amended the 
republics constitution to give it the power to veto soviet laws 
estonian officials have used that veto power cautiously 
on tuesday they postponed plans to override two controversial 
nationwide decrees limiting demonstrations and dissent deciding to 
ignore the decrees and instead enforce a more liberal estonian law 
</TEXT>
