<TEXT>
the communist party chief in tibet known for his 
support of relatively liberal policies in that region has been 
removed from his post an official spokesman said wednesday 
wu jinghua appointed to the job in may 1985 was replaced by hu 
jintao head of the party committee in guizhou province since july 
1985 
a western traveler and a tibetan switchboard operator meanwhile 
said the situation in lhasa tibets provincial capital was calm 
two clashes in as many years between proindependence tibetans and 
chinese forces killed dozens of people 
in beijing zhang wenyuan spokesman for the liaison office of 
the chinese communist party said wus removal was part of a 
normal job rotation and denied the switch was related to unrest 
in tibet 
zhang said the transfer had been made recently although he 
declined to specify when he said he did not know what job if any 
wu was to hold following his dismissal 
a chinese source contacted wednesday night in beijing said the 
move was made dec 1 the source described the new party leader hu 
as a conservative meaning that he would likely adopt a harder 
approach than wu toward tibetan proindependence activities 
rumors have circulated since summer that wu was set to be sacked 
because he had not cracked down hard enough on the proindependence 
protests 
antichinese demonstrations began in lhasa in late september and 
october 1987 resulting in the deaths of at least 14 people 
on march 5 proindependence tibetans clashed again with police 
and western travelers quoted tibetans as saying at least 24 people 
died chinese reports said hundreds were arrested in october and 
march 
since march sketchy reports from lhasa have described the city 
as tense although little violence has been reported 
on wednesday the western traveler contacted by telephone said he 
had not seen many soldiers on the street he said the mood in the 
city was mellow 
the telephone operator also reported the city was calm 
while head of the party in tibet wu has been credited with 
enacting relatively liberal policies said one source close to the 
dismissed leader 
during the cultural revolution which lasted from 1966 to 1976 
bands of ultraradical red guards destroyed tibets buddhist temples 
and killed thousands of monks in an attempt to wipe out tibets 
culture vilified as feudal and backward 
the use of the tibetan language was banned in schools and 
tibetans were forbidden from traveling within the region unless they 
first obtained a permit 
with the end of the cultural revolution chinas policies in 
tibet moderated somewhat 
under wu tibetans were allowed to use their native tongue in 
schools and were given limited freedom to travel within the huge 
region which borders india nepal bhutan and burma 
wu the source said was also responsible for encouraging the 
central government to develop tibets economy and opening lhasas 
first university 
china claims sovereignty over tibet dating to the 13th century 
chinese troops entered tibet in 1950 nine years later the 
crushed an antichinese uprising and tibets religious and spiritual 
leader the dalai lama fled to exile in india 
after decades of accusing the chinese of genocide the dalai lama 
recently adopted a more conciliatory tone in a speech in 
strasbourg france in june he said he would accept a chinese troop 
presence in tibet and chinese management of tibets foreign 
relations if china let tibet run its internal affairs 
china in september proposed to meet with the dalai lama but 
stressed that the strasbourg proposals could not be used as a basis 
for the talks 
the dalai lama has proposed that the two sides meet in geneva in 
january china has yet to respond 
