<TEXT>
injections of a drug that has been the mainstay of 
malaria treatment are safe despite recent concerns about the safety 
of the injected form according to a new report 
tests conducted on 58 children with severe malaria in gambia 
showed no reason to abandon injections of the drug called 
chloroquine according to a report in thursdays new england journal 
of medicine 
the drug the worlds most widely prescribed malaria medicine is 
an important medicine in poor parts of the world where malaria is 
common because it is cheap widely available well tolerated and 
cures the disease quickly 
the drug is used in both pill and injection form to treat and 
prevent the disease which kills an estimated 2 million to 3 million 
people annually 
recently a world health organization report raised toxicity 
concerns about the safety of the injected form of the drug in 
patients who cannot take chloroquine pills because of coma or 
vomiting 
in the recent study dr nicholas j white of the bangkok 
hospital for tropical diseases in thailand tested seven different 
treatment regimens in 58 children with severe malaria in gambia 
they found that continuous intravenous infusions of the drug over 
30 hours worked well 
