<TEXT>
the supreme court studying the fbis power to 
keep criminal records secret was told wednesday that individuals 
have no privacy right to conceal records of arrests and convictions 
kevin t baine representing a cbs news reporter and the 
reporters committee for freedom of the press conceded that 
information about old arrests that did not lead to convictions could 
paint an unfair picture about someone 
but that doesnt make the information private baine said 
roy t englert a justice department lawyer who argued the reagan 
administration position said the fbi should be allowed to exclude 
socalled rap sheets from disclosure under the freedom of 
information act 
there is a balancing between the public interest and privacy 
rights englert said 
he chose an example from les miserables a famous work of 
french literature and now a hit broadway musical to underscore his 
point 
jean valjean the hero of the work may be entitled to privacy 
for his conviction for stealing bread years earlier englert said 
the justices are studying the administrations bid to scuttle an 
foia lawsuit by cbs news reporter robert schakne and the reporters 
committee 
schakne in 1978 sought all fbi records of the arrests 
indictments and court dispositions of any charges against four 
brothers three of whom were identified as associates of reputed 
pennsylvania crime boss russell bufalino 
schakne sought the fbi records on william phillip samuel and 
charles medico 
he was trying to determine if they had criminal records because 
their firm medico industries inc had received lucrative defense 
contracts with the help of former rep daniel j flood dpa 
flood pleaded guilty to conspiracy in 1980 and was placed on 
probation in connection with charges he accepted 50000 in bribes 
the reporters committee later filed a request similar to 
schaknes for the fbi records 
the fbi maintains rap sheets on some 25 million americans 
compiling arrest and conviction records supplied by federal state 
and local law enforcement agencies 
the pennsylvania crime commission in 1980 identified phillip 
angelo and william medico as members of the bufalino crime family 
the commission said bufalino regularly visited the medico family 
business in wilkesbarre pa over a 20year period 
the fbi released information about the late william medico said 
it had no records on phillip and samuel also deceased and refused 
to release its file on charles medico on grounds it would violate 
his privacy rights 
the us circuit court of appeals here ruled last year that the 
1966 foia law does not exempt such records from disclosure 
some justices expressed skepticism wednesday over the 
administrations bid to reverse the appeals court decision 
there is an expectation of privacy that a public record will 
not be discovered justice antonin scalia asked englert 
i thought the underpinning of the first amendment is that the 
government will not decide what information is more useful to the 
citizenry scalia said im not inclined for the government to 
make that determination 
the court is expected to announce its decision in the case by 
july 
the case is us department of justice vs reporters committee 
871379 
