western europe welcomed mikhail s gorbachevs 
pledge wednesday to reduce soviet conventional forces but tempered 
the praise with warnings that the warsaw pact still will have 
military superiority over nato 
television in communist poland carried footage without comment of 
the soviet leader announcing at the united nations in new york that 
he will reduce troop levels by 500000 and remove 5000 tanks and 
other arms within two years 
jacek czaputowicz cofounder of polands antinuclear peace and 
freedom movement said in warsaw the announcement could be the 
first step in pulling soviet troops out of poland 
east germany czechoslovakia and hungary from whose territory 
50000 soviet soldiers and 5000 tanks are to be withdrawn made no 
comment 
an official statement in london said prime minister margaret 
thatcher the most hawkish head of a nato government warmly 
welcomed gorbachevs pledge and will discuss it with him next week 
during his stop in britain en route home 
nato secretarygeneral manfred woerner said in brussels it 
seems to be a step in the right direction but that considerable 
imbalances would remain 
the 500share index of londons financial times reversed a slump 
and rose 199 points to close at 99729 the dollar jumped initially 
on hopes a soviet cutback would mean reciprocal us defense 
reductions and a shrinking of the american deficit but fell back 
when dealers realized it was too soon to know 
widespread selling of gold resulted from the dollars surge 
pushing the bullion price in london and zurich down 4 to about 423 
an ounce 
mrs thatchers first reaction was that she warmly welcomed the 
cuts in forces and armaments proposed by mr gorbachev as an 
important step toward securing a better balance of conventional 
forces in europe in view of the soviets present overwhelming 
superiority said a statement from her office at 10 downing street 
chancellor helmut kohl now sees a good chance to reach 
conventional weapons stability in europe said friedhelm ost 
chief spokesman for the west german government 
rupert scholz kohls defense minister said gorbachev must 
follow up with actual and verifiable withdrawal of troops and 
reduction of forces 
franz vranitzky chancellor of austria called gorbachevs 
statement a courageous and constructive proposal 
former british defense secretaries michael heseltine 
conservative and denis healey labor disagreed in a television 
debate about how enthusiastically to welcome gorbachevs pledge 
