african national congress 
leader nelson mandela was transferred wednesday evening from a 
clinic to live at a house on a prison farm outside cape town 
aside from stays in hospitals it marked the first time since 
1962 that the 70yearold prisoner south africas most widely known 
black leader has lived outside a cell 
prison officials said mandelas wife winnie children and 
grandchildren would have unlimited access to mandela at his new 
quarters in a staff house on prison property the onestory house 
has a patio flower garden and swimming pool 
but mrs mandela rejected the offer and said she will continue to 
make the standard 40minute visits to her husband until he is freed 
according to the familys lawyer ismail ayob 
the government has been under intense domestic and international 
pressure to release mandela unconditionally but officials have 
indicated that his outright release is not imminent and that 
restraints on him will be eased in stages so the government can 
assess the political impact of his possible freedom 
some opposition leaders criticized the governments move 
dullah omar a human rights lawyer who leads the banned united 
democratic front called the move utterly disgraceful and 
callous 
what we were looking forward to was his release not a transfer 
from a clinic back to prison he said 
zach de beer leader of the antiapartheid progressive federal 
party welcomed the transfer on humanitarian grounds but added 
unless mr mandela is given the freedom to participate in the 
political process of the country he is denied the opportunity of 
making his contribution towards the future 
the transfer was announced by justice minister kobie coetsee who 
said mandela was moved to a suitable comfortable and properly 
secured home at the victor verster prison in paarl 
mandela has been imprisoned since 1962 and is serving a life 
sentence for plotting a sabotage campaign against the 
whitecontrolled government 
the outlawed anc is the largest guerrilla organization fighting 
the government and apartheid south africas policy of racial 
segregation 
mandela has rejected the governments repeated offers to release 
him if he renounces violence or live in a tribal homeland he has 
said the government should renounce violence end apartheid and 
legalize the anc 
last august mandela was diagnosed with tuberculosis and 
transferred to a hospital from cape towns pollsmoor prison later 
he was moved to the constantiaberg clinic a luxury private hospital 
near pollsmoor and coetsee announced on nov 24 that mandela would 
not be returned to pollsmoor when his recuperation was complete 
ayob quoted mrs mandela as saying that mandelas transfer is 
clearly a response to the domestic and international pressure for 
his release 
i do not intend taking more than the normal 40minute visit 
ive been allowed in the past until all political prisoners have the 
same privilege she said in a statement provided by ayob 
south africa is still under a state of emergency and there are 
thousands of political prisoners and detainees and large numbers of 
leaders organizations and the media remain restricted mrs 
mandela said in the statement 
there was no indication that other visitors such as the media 
would be allowed access to mandela 
mandelas transfer to a private home is one of a series of moves 
by the government in the past two weeks aimed at easing 
international pressure on south africa 
the government has given tentative approval to a peace pact that 
would bring independence to namibia commuted the controversial 
death sentences of six blacks known as the sharpeville six and 
freed two other prominent longserving black prisoners anc leader 
harry gwala and zeph mothopeng president of the rival 
panafricanist congress 
but the government has given no indication that it is willing to 
negotiate with freed black leaders on their demands for oneperson 
onevote democracy 
under apartheid south africas 26 million blacks have no vote in 
national affairs the 5 million whites control the economy and 
maintain separate districts schools and health services 
