soviet president mikhail s gorbachev 
declared wednesday that his government no longer holds political 
prisoners and that it has applied strict time limits on the use of 
state secrecy as a reason for refusing jews permission to emigrate 
although western observers generally acknowledge there has been a 
dramatic reduction in the number of political prisoners since 
gorbachev rose to power human rights groups still count about 150 
people said to be held solely because of their political or 
religious beliefs 
gorbachev promised the problem of exit from and entry to our 
country including the question of leaving it for family 
reunification is being dealt with in a humane spirit but he gave 
no indication the soviet union is prepared to open its borders to 
unrestricted travel or emigration 
in places of confinement there are no persons convicted for 
their political or religious beliefs the soviet leader told the 
united nations general assembly but he added that his statement did 
not apply to those who committed actual criminal offenses or state 
crimes such as espionage sabotage terrorism et cetera whatever 
their political or ideological beliefs 
secretary of state george shultz said the soviet union has 
released a great many political prisoners but such people still 
exist differences of opinion exist on whether a person is in prison 
because of his political views or because of a violation of law he 
said 
but shultz said he thought it possible to a construct a procedure 
in which we will go through with them namebyname the people on 
our list to determine whether a person should be released 
the united states and human rights groups have focused attention 
on two soviet laws gorbachev didnt mention specifically but which 
make it a crime to slander the soviet state or engage in antisoviet 
agitation the soviets have indicated they will modify or eliminate 
those statutes in a rewrite of their criminal code now under way 
nobel laureate andrei sakharov the wellknown soviet dissident 
whom gorbachev released from internal exile two years ago contends 
that an unspecified number of soviets remain in prisons or labor 
camps for their political or religious views 
one of the reasons for refusal to leave is a persons knowledge 
of secrets gorbachev told his audience strictly warranted time 
limitations on the secrecy rule will now be applied this 
removes from the agenda the problem of the socalled refuseniks 
refusenik is a journalists term used to describe soviets usually 
jews who have been refused permission to emigrate 
alexander yakovlev a member of the communist partys ruling 
politburo and a top adviser to gorbachev told an american peace 
coalition after the speech that he does not believe that there are 
any serious obstacles to those who want to emigrate 
he said the process of disarmament has not reached a stage at 
which it is possible to let those with military secrets leave the 
country but yakovlev contended there are fewer than 46 such cases 
remaining 
this is unfortunate he added but it is another motivation 
to disarm 
foreign ministry spokesman gennady i gerasimov claimed this 
is a problem that has disappeared with the establishment of an 
appeal procedure to permit review of refuseniks cases 
jerry strober a spokesman for the national conference on soviet 
jewry told the associated press after gorbachevs speech that his 
group has documented 1987 soviet jewish families who have been 
refused exit visas for more than five years a significant number of 
whom have been told they were not permitted to leave because they 
once had access to state secrets 
strober noted that gorbachev said four years ago no one would be 
held more than 10 years for having had access to secrets but at 
least 512 of those still on the conferences list have waited more 
than 10 years for permission to leave he said 
amnesty international the londonbased human rights 
organization has said in recent weeks it has information on 150 
soviets imprisoned solely for the nonviolent exercise of their 
fundamental human rights 
and a lay roman catholic organization called puebla institute 
counts 156 soviets it says are jailed for their religious beliefs 
the two lists overlap but are not identical 
