<TEXT>
californias supreme court agreed wednesday 
to hear insurers lawsuits challenging the proposition 103 rate 
reduction initiative but allowed immediate enforcement of all major 
provisions except a 20 percent rollback in auto insurance rates 
the portions of the measure that the court allowed to take effect 
will force companies to base insurance rates primarily on a drivers 
record and experience and repeal an exemption from state antitrust 
laws for insurance companies 
harvey rosenfield chairman of voter revolt and author of the 
measure said he was disappointed that the court did not also allow 
the rate rollback but he said he was excited that some provisions 
will take effect 
one insurance industry official said he was disappointed that the 
courts prior stay on the entire measure had been modified at all 
but said it was a positive sign that the court had blocked the 
rollback provision 
at first blush were pleased that the court will hear our 
arguments but we feel the briefing schedule is more relaxed than 
wed like said john kozero a spokesman for firemans fund 
insurance cos no date has been set for a hearing and we hoped 
for a speedy resolution to the case 
the justices indicated they would not hear oral arguments until 
february the court voted 61 to hear the case with justice stanley 
mosk dissenting 
attorney general john van de kamp who is defending the measure 
in court called the courts action the first step toward full 
implementation of proposition 103 
the court had blocked implementation of proposition 103 on nov 
10 two days after voters approved it it was the only one of five 
insurancerelated initiatives to pass 
in wednesdays order the court left its stay in place for only 
two of the measures numerous provisions 
one which is the central target of the lawsuits would reduce 
motor vehicle and property insurance rates 20 percent below november 
1987 levels and freeze them until november 1989 the only 
exemptions would be for insurers that could show a substantial 
threat of insolvency 
the insurance companies lawsuits contend the rollback and freeze 
are an unconstitutional confiscation of the insurers property 
because they do not take into account a companys continued ability 
to make a profit 
the other provision that remains blocked would require mailing of 
notices to announce the formation of a nonprofit corporation to 
advocate the interests of insurance consumers insurers contend the 
corporation violates restrictions in the california constitution 
the provisions that will be allowed to take effect include a 
requirement that auto insurance rates be based primarily on a 
drivers record and experience rather than place of residence a 
ban on cancellation or nonrenewal of auto policies except for 
failure to pay fraud or an increase in the risk and a repeal of 
the insurance industrys exemption from state antitrust laws 
the courts order appeared to support the position of the state 
attorney general and private sponsors that a stay of all portions of 
the measure was excessive because most do not threaten the companies 
with any immediate measurable financial harm 
the insurers lawsuits did not attack all provisions of 
proposition 103 but argued that the entire initiative should be 
thrown out if the rate rollback and freeze are declared 
unconstitutional 
