<TEXT>
the days of lower oil prices will end by 1992 and 
the coming decade will be marked by higher prices that will slow 
economic growth in the united states a study by two economists at 
the federal reserve bank of dallas says 
stephen brown and keith phillips contend that falling demand for 
oil in the 1980s has had more to do with the collapse in oil prices 
than the disarray in the organization of petroleum exporting 
countries 
and they say in a study to be published next month that growing 
demand in the 1990s will push opec countries to full capacity and 
prices above 30 a barrel 
people planning on building big cars in the next decade may be 
headed in the wrong direction brown said in an interview but 
it wont be as bad as the the 70s where we saw sharp price 
increases that really nailed the economy 
the economists said however that those in the currently 
depressed oil business shouldnt begin dancing in the streets 
after adjusting for inflation the higher price level will still 
amount to only 60 percent to 80 percent of the peak price of oil 
reached in 1981 they said 
by 1992 oil prices should begin rising and by the year 2000 
oil prices will reach 35 to 40 a barrel or more than double the 
current level they predict 
i really dont think well see a return to the boom times of 
1981 in the oil industry brown said but we should see some 
increases as early as 92 barring opec action and definitely by 
95 by 1995 the price will have to be in the neighborhood of 25 
a barrel because of the demand 
in the united states alone brown and phillips said oil 
consumption will increase between 21 percent and 95 percent 
annually 
current price levels encourage consumption and discourage the 
development of alternative resources or conservation efforts in the 
next decade the growth of world economies will continue to spur 
demand and pressure prices higher the economists suggest 
under nearly all of our scenarios the growth in oil 
consumption pushes opec close to full capacity between late 1992 and 
early 1995 said the study which will be published in january in 
the feds regional economic review as opec nears full capacity 
prices are likely to rise sharply 
the study assumes no major disruptions in oil production or 
artificial pushes such as a resumption of the iraniraq war or a 
sharp increase in taxes on oil 
rising oil prices will strengthen economic growth in 
energyexporting countries while hindering economic growth in 
energyimporting countries like the united states the study says 
and as in the past the effects will cut unevenly through this 
country 
energyproducing regions like texas and louisiana will benefit 
while energyconsuming areas like the northeast will suffer 
currently production of oil exceeds worldwide demand thus 
triggering the fall in prices to between 15 and 16 a barrel last 
month opec agreed to try to limit its production and bolster oil 
prices but the cartels past attempts at output restraint have 
failed 
