<TEXT>
michael boskin the conservative economist who 
will be the chief economic adviser to the bush administration is a 
longtime proponent of farreaching changes in social security and 
other benefit programs that boskin labels welfare for the 
wealthy 
in a book last year boskin wrote that president reagans 
successor can control spending only by a major attack on 
middleclass entitlementse for the wealthy simply can no longer be afforded 
boskin wrote in reagan 
welfarand the economy the successes failures 
and unfinished agenda 
more costconscious spending on these programs will 
preserve benefits for the needy argued boskin named by 
presidentelect george bush on tuesday as chairman of the council of 
economic advisers 
the 43yearold stanford university economics professor is 
certain to be questioned closely about his views on the politically 
sensitive subject of social security during his confirmation 
hearings before the senate banking committee 
boskin in his book cited social security the medicare program 
that pays the medical bills of the elderly and farm subsidies as 
prime targets for cuts 
these programs are hard to curtail precisely beending curbs without 
any higher taxes 
critics have derisively referred to the proposal as a flexible 
fraud but bush has been insistent that he will not raise taxes to 
curb the deficit 
under the flexible freeze plan overall government spending would 
be allowed to grow only at the rate of inflation some programs 
would face sharper cuts to provide money to allow others to grow at 
a faster pace 
in his book last year and in a 1986 book too many promises 
boskin offered far different advice about social security urging a 
sharp curtailment in real growth of future benefits especially for 
higher income retirees 
while boskin has been a prominent critic of the existing social 
security program for more than a decade he parts company with 
conservatives who favor turning the system over to private auspices 
instead boskin has proposed creating a twotiered pension system 
and additional incentives for more private savings for retirement 
in the first tier everyone would receive monthly checks at 
retirement based on a dollarfordollar return on their social 
security payroll taxes and the taxes paid by their employers the 
benefit formula which now provides a proportionally bigger return 
for lowincome workers would be the same for all 
there would be no spouses benefit but husbands and wives would 
share earnings credits equally 
the second tier would be a welfare program for the elderly poor 
financed from general revenues instead of the payroll tax 
boskin credits social security as a major contributor to the 
relief of economic distress and hardship among the elderly but he 
criticized the program for channeling funds to those who could by 
no means be considered needy paid out of taxes partially levied on 
low and middleincome people 
in his review of reagans record on the economy boskin called 
the string of huge budget deficits the major flaw in the reagan 
program 
he wrote that the next administration will need to control 
spending by tackling not only social security but also medicare 
benefits for higherincome people farm subsidies and government 
loans to students and others 
while bush has vowed to leave social security untouched his 
choice as budget director richard darman already has indicated 
that the new administration will be looking for budget savings in 
medicare 
without changes medicare is projected to cost the federal 
government 977 billion in fiscal 1990 which begins next october 
that is a 145 percent increase from the current fiscal year 
reflecting growth that is almost four times faster than the expected 
inflation rate 
