<DOCNO> AP881207-0292 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
college endowments buffeted by the october 
1987 stock market crash still managed to post a tiny gain in the 
last fiscal year a college business group reported wednesday 
the national association of college and university business 
officers said preliminary results from its survey of 100 major 
endowment funds indicated an average gain of 02 percent for the 
year ended last june 1 
that was down from a 138 percent gain for the campus endowments 
in fiscal 1987 the group said it beat the minus71 percent return 
on the standard amp poors 500 during the year government and 
corporate bonds rose 75 percent during the same year 
the business officers have tracked major campus endowments 
annually since 1971 
caspa l harris executive vice president of the association 
said to the extent that one can point to a single reason for the 
sharp decline in endowment returns the october crash is 
responsible 
endowment funds are invested primarily in publicly traded 
securities and history suggests that the market values of such 
securities fluctuate widely based on changes in investor 
psychology he said 
the preliminary report did not list the endowments by name or 
size the final report will be out in february 
almost half the funds in the typical endowment were invested in 
stocks and 29 percent in fixed income securities thirteen percent 
was in cash and cash equivalents the rest was invested in a variety 
of ways including 12 percent put up for venture capital projects 
