<DOCNO> AP881207-0297 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a denver broker in penny stocks has filed suit in 
the us supreme court challenging the constitutionality of the 
enforcement powers of the securities and exchange commission 
the broker blinder robinson and co inc is asking the court 
to decide whether the agencys enforcement powers violate the 
constitution 
the sec issued an injunction in 1982 against the company which 
alleged that blinder robinson violated securities laws by 
underwriting stock in american leisure corp a casino based in new 
jersey 
blinder robinson said in the suit filed late last month that the 
securities and exchange commission has extremely broad powers and 
alleged that the agency has overstepped its bounds the company is 
asking the supreme court to clarify which branch of government the 
executive judicial or legislative has responsibility for the 
commission 
there is no limit on whom the sec may investigate and 
prosecute the company said in its court complaint 
the firm alleges that this violates the separation of powers 
provided in the constitution 
the company also complained in its brief that there have been no 
allegations of misconduct or violations since the court order was 
first issued but the injunction is continuing to harm the companys 
operations 
blinder robinson has been the target of a number of federal 
investigations recently federal agents raided the companys 
offices as part of an investigation into international stock fraud 
the company also faces a possible fine from the national 
association of securities dealers in a separate unrelated case 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

